The paper discusses a method for evaluating the scientific credit of papers and scientists, which involves analyzing author-paper bipartite networks. This suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-categories of social networks (cs.SOC), information retrieval (cs.IR), or cybernetics (cs.CYBER). Additionally, the paper mentions conducting experiments on publications in econophysics, which could place it in the sub-category of digital libraries (cs.DL) or social and information networks (cs.SI).
